{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17415073","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17415073"},"attributes":{"position":45,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T09:01:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T09:01:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100"}},"session":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2347"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17504599","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17504599"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:17:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:17:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2347"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionSessions/1261100"},"attributes":{"startedAt":"2025-09-28T07:52:04+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T10:28:52+09:30","sessionType":"qbank","questionStatus":"all","difficulty":[],"timeLimit":null,"questionCount":62,"questionsAnswered":61,"marksTotal":61,"marksAttainable":61,"marksAttempted":61,"finishedAt":"2025-09-28T09:15:31+09:30","resultsAvailable":true,"score":0.2,"questionsCorrect":12,"marksCorrect":12},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"pack":{"data":{"type":"packs","id":"5"}},"exam":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questions","id":"2347","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2347"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.18,0.77,0,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2347"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105220"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2347","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2347"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2347"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87647"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"147"},{"type":"tags","id":"205"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"12917"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1293"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1297"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8852"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8909"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15831"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15864"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16252"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105220","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/105220"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 27-year-old woman who is ten weeks pregnant presents to the Emergency Department with worsening shortness of breath over the last 24 hours. She has a history of severe asthma and has been using her salbutamol inhaler more frequently over the past week without improvement. She reports wheezing and chest tightness. She has no fever or productive cough. Her last severe exacerbation was six months ago, requiring a short course of oral prednisolone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears distressed. Her pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 130/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 28/min, oxygen saturation 92% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. On auscultation, there is widespread wheeze throughout both lung fields. Her peak expiratory flow rate is 55% of her personal best. The team have initiated oxygen therapy.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Withhold corticosteroids due to pregnancy risks","Administer nebulised salbutamol only","Administer oral prednisolone and nebulised salbutamol","Recommend termination of pregnancy","Administer intravenous aminophylline"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn this case of a pregnant woman presenting with a severe asthma exacerbation, the most appropriate next step in management is to \u003Cstrong\u003Eadminister oral prednisolone\u003C/strong\u003E. While there are always concerns about medication use during pregnancy, the risks of uncontrolled asthma to both the mother and fetus far outweigh the potential risks of corticosteroid use.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWithholding corticosteroids due to pregnancy risks\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate. Uncontrolled asthma during pregnancy can lead to serious complications including preeclampsia, preterm birth, and low birth weight. The benefits of treating severe asthma exacerbations with systemic corticosteroids outweigh the potential risks to the fetus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdministering nebulised salbutamol only\u003C/strong\u003E would be insufficient for a severe exacerbation. While bronchodilators are an important component of asthma management, this patient\u0027s condition warrants more aggressive treatment including systemic corticosteroids.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERecommending termination of pregnancy\u003C/strong\u003E is entirely inappropriate and unethical. Asthma, even when severe, can be managed effectively during pregnancy without resorting to such extreme measures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdministering intravenous aminophylline\u003C/strong\u003E is not a first-line treatment for asthma exacerbations, especially in pregnancy. It has a narrow therapeutic window and potential for significant side effects. Systemic corticosteroids are preferred.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management of asthma during pregnancy follows similar principles to non-pregnant patients. Inhaled corticosteroids are considered safe and are the mainstay of controller therapy. For acute exacerbations, short courses of systemic corticosteroids can be used when necessary. The goal is to maintain good asthma control, as this leads to the best outcomes for both mother and fetus. After the acute management, it would be important to review and optimize this patient\u0027s ongoing asthma management plan to prevent future exacerbations.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Inhaled corticosteroids are safe and recommended for asthma management during pregnancy.","Oral corticosteroids can be used for severe asthma exacerbations in pregnancy when benefits outweigh risks.","Uncontrolled asthma poses greater risks to the fetus than potential side effects of asthma medications."],"references":["Lim A, Hussainy SY, Abramson MJ. Asthma drugs in pregnancy and lactation. Aust Prescr. 2013;36(5):150-3. Available from: https://doi.org/10.18773/austprescr.2013.061","Bravo-Solarte DC, Garcia-Guaqueta DP, Chiarella SE. Asthma in pregnancy. Allergy Asthma Proc. 2023 Jan 1;44(1):24-34. doi: 10.2500/aap.2023.44.220077. PMID: 36719688; PMCID: PMC9809179. Avaialble from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/36719688/","Shebl E, Chakraborty RK. Asthma in Pregnancy. [Updated 2023 Jun 26]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK532283/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87647"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2347"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87647","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/87647"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-08T12:12:04+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-08T12:12:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"ty